Morhof (Polyhistor, torn. i. lib. a. cap. 7) speaks of a work, published in Hungary in 1663, by one John Beyer, entitled ‘F ilum Labyrinthi wel Cynosura, sive Lux mentium universalis,' dte, in which the author attempted to expound tbe Baconian philosophy. ‘Verum obscurat potius Verulamii sensus omnemque philosophiam, quam ut lumen aliquod accendat.’ This fact is interesting as shewing that the fame of Bacon’s philosophical reform had reached even remote countries like Hungary.

On the possible, or, perhaps, probable influence of Bacon's writings on the institution of scientific societies abroad, I shall have occasion to speak in a note on the next division of my subject.
